{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614416"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:45:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:45:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16366"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16366"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0,0.61,0.22,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9057"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116493"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9057"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98486"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"5932"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21536"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22743"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116493"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDiplopia (double vision) can be classified as either horizontal or vertical depending on the relative displacement of the two images. Understanding the actions of extraocular muscles is crucial for determining the cause.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the muscle imbalance that typically causes vertical diplopia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Loss of lateral rectus with unopposed medial rectus action","Loss of medial rectus with unopposed lateral rectus action","Loss of superior oblique with unopposed inferior oblique action","Loss of inferior oblique with unopposed superior oblique action","Loss of lateral rectus with unopposed superior oblique action"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eloss of superior oblique with unopposed inferior oblique action\u003C/strong\u003E. The superior oblique muscle normally functions to intort and depress the eye. When it is paralysed (as in fourth cranial nerve palsy), the unopposed action of the inferior oblique muscle causes the affected eye to drift upward, resulting in vertical diplopia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of lateral rectus with unopposed medial rectus action\u003C/strong\u003E causes horizontal diplopia as these muscles control horizontal eye movements. \u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of medial rectus with unopposed lateral rectus action\u003C/strong\u003E also results in horizontal rather than vertical diplopia. \u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of inferior oblique with unopposed superior oblique action\u003C/strong\u003E would cause downward drift of the eye but is less common. \u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of lateral rectus with unopposed superior oblique action\u003C/strong\u003E combines muscles with different primary actions and is not a typical cause of diplopia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVertical diplopia most commonly occurs with superior oblique muscle paralysis due to fourth cranial nerve palsy, which may result from head trauma, diabetes, or other neurological conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Vertical diplopia occurs when there is imbalance between muscles that control vertical eye movements, particularly the superior and inferior oblique muscles.","The superior oblique muscle intorts and depresses the eye, while the inferior oblique muscle extorts and elevates the eye.","Loss of superior oblique function (e.g. fourth cranial nerve palsy) results in unopposed inferior oblique action causing vertical diplopia."],"references":["Jain S. Diplopia: Diagnosis and management. Clin Med (Lond). 2022 Mar;22(2):104-106. doi: 10.7861/clinmed.2022-0045. PMID: 35304368; PMCID: PMC8966821.","Dinkin M. Diagnostic approach to diplopia. Continuum (Minneap Minn). 2014 Aug;20(4 Neuro-ophthalmology):942-65. doi: 10.1212/01.CON.0000453310.52390.58. PMID: 25099102; PMCID: PMC10563939.","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98486"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16366"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98486"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T11:26:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T11:28:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9057"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116493"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"positio